\section{Introduction}

\subsection{Overview of Three-Phase Systems}

Three-phase electrical power systems are the backbone of modern electrical distribution networks worldwide. They offer significant advantages over single-phase systems, including:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Higher power transmission efficiency}: Three-phase systems can transmit $\sqrt{3}$ times more power using the same amount of conductor material compared to single-phase systems.
    \item \textbf{Constant power delivery}: The instantaneous power in a balanced three-phase system is constant, reducing vibrations in electrical machines.
    \item \textbf{Rotating magnetic field}: Essential for the operation of three-phase induction motors, which are the workhorses of industry.
    \item \textbf{Economic advantages}: Lower conductor costs and smaller equipment sizes for the same power rating.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Key Concepts}

\subsubsection{Phase Sequence}

The phase sequence (ABC or positive sequence) refers to the order in which the three phases reach their maximum values. This is crucial for:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Motor rotation direction
    \item Power flow direction in generators
    \item Proper synchronization in parallel operation
\end{itemize}

The voltage phasors in an ABC sequence are separated by $120^\circ$ electrical:
\begin{align}
    \ve{U}_{AN} &= U_{ph} \phase{0} \\
    \ve{U}_{BN} &= U_{ph} \phase{-120} \\
    \ve{U}_{CN} &= U_{ph} \phase{+120}
\end{align}

\subsubsection{Star (Y) vs Delta ($\Delta$) Connections}

\textbf{Star Connection:}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Provides a neutral point for unbalanced loads
    \item Line voltage: $U_L = \sqrt{3} \cdot U_{ph}$
    \item Line current equals phase current: $I_L = I_{ph}$
    \item Used in distribution systems (e.g., 400/230V)
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Delta Connection:}
\begin{itemize}
    \item No neutral point available
    \item Line voltage equals phase voltage: $U_L = U_{ph}$
    \item Line current: $I_L = \sqrt{3} \cdot I_{ph}$
    \item Used for motor windings and high-power loads
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Importance of Power Factor}

The power factor ($\cos \varphi$) is a critical parameter in AC systems:

\begin{equation}
    \text{Power Factor} = \cos \varphi = \frac{P}{S} = \frac{\text{Active Power}}{\text{Apparent Power}}
\end{equation}

\textbf{Why is it important?}
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Utility charges}: Many utilities impose penalties for low power factor ($<0.95$)
    \item \textbf{Conductor sizing}: Low power factor requires larger conductors to carry the same active power
    \item \textbf{Voltage drop}: Higher currents cause greater voltage drops in distribution lines
    \item \textbf{Equipment rating}: Transformers and generators must be rated for apparent power, not just active power
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Power factor correction} using capacitor banks is essential to:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item Reduce reactive power demand
    \item Minimize line losses ($I^2 R$ losses)
    \item Avoid utility penalties
    \item Increase system capacity without upgrading infrastructure
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Objectives of This Report}

This report presents a comprehensive analysis of three-phase systems, covering:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Exercise 1}: Balanced star-connected load with power factor correction
    \item \textbf{Exercise 2}: Balanced delta-connected load with equivalence analysis
    \item \textbf{Exercise 3}: Unbalanced star system with neutral current analysis
\end{enumerate}

Each exercise demonstrates the fundamental relationships, calculation methods, and practical considerations essential for power system engineering.

\subsection{Methodology}

All calculations follow these steps:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item Define system parameters and configuration
    \item Calculate impedances and reactances
    \item Determine voltage and current phasors
    \item Calculate power quantities (P, Q, S)
    \item Verify relationships and balance conditions
    \item Design corrective measures if required
\end{enumerate}

MATLAB code is provided for numerical analysis and visualization of phasor diagrams and power triangles.


\section{Exercise 1: Balanced Three-Phase Star System}

\subsection{Problem Statement}

A balanced three-phase, 4-wire system supplies a star-connected inductive load. The system must be analyzed for voltages, currents, power consumption, and power factor correction requirements.

\subsection{Given Data}

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{lcc}
\toprule
\textbf{Parameter} & \textbf{Value} & \textbf{Unit} \\
\midrule
Line voltage, $U_L$ & 230 & V \\
Frequency, $f$ & 60 & Hz \\
Resistance per phase, $R$ & 12 & $\Omega$ \\
Inductance per phase, $L$ & 0.05 & H \\
Phase sequence & ABC & - \\
Connection type & Star with neutral & - \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{System specifications for Exercise 1}
\end{table}

\subsection{Calculations}

\subsubsection{Step 1: Inductive Reactance}

The inductive reactance at the operating frequency is:

\begin{equation}
    X_L = 2\pi f L = 2\pi \times 60 \times 0.05 = \SI{18.8496}{\ohm}
\end{equation}

\subsubsection{Step 2: Phase Impedance}

The complex impedance per phase:

\begin{equation}
    \ve{Z}_{ph} = R + jX_L = 12 + j18.8496 \, \Omega
\end{equation}

Magnitude:
\begin{equation}
    |\ve{Z}_{ph}| = \sqrt{R^2 + X_L^2} = \sqrt{12^2 + 18.8496^2} = \SI{22.3453}{\ohm}
\end{equation}

Phase angle (impedance angle):
\begin{equation}
    \varphi = \arctan\left(\frac{X_L}{R}\right) = \arctan\left(\frac{18.8496}{12}\right) = 57.52^\circ
\end{equation}

Polar form:
\begin{equation}
    \ve{Z}_{ph} = 22.3453 \phase{57.52} \, \Omega
\end{equation}

\subsubsection{Step 3: Phase Voltages}

For a star connection, the phase voltage is:

\begin{equation}
    U_{ph} = \frac{U_L}{\sqrt{3}} = \frac{230}{1.7321} = \SI{132.79}{V}
\end{equation}

Taking $\ve{U}_{AN}$ as the reference phasor ($\phase{0}$):

\begin{align}
    \ve{U}_{AN} &= 132.79 \phase{0} \, \text{V} \\
    \ve{U}_{BN} &= 132.79 \phase{-120} \, \text{V} \\
    \ve{U}_{CN} &= 132.79 \phase{+120} \, \text{V}
\end{align}

\textbf{Verification:}
\begin{equation}
    U_L = \sqrt{3} \times U_{ph} = 1.7321 \times 132.79 = 230 \, \text{V} \quad \checkmark
\end{equation}

\subsubsection{Step 4: Phase Currents}

The magnitude of phase current:

\begin{equation}
    I_{ph} = \frac{U_{ph}}{|\ve{Z}_{ph}|} = \frac{132.79}{22.3453} = \SI{5.9418}{A}
\end{equation}

Since the load is inductive, the current \textbf{lags} the voltage by $\varphi = 57.52^\circ$.

Phase current phasors:

\begin{align}
    \ve{I}_A &= \frac{\ve{U}_{AN}}{\ve{Z}_{ph}} = \frac{132.79\phase{0}}{22.3453\phase{57.52}} = 5.9418\phase{-57.52} \, \text{A} \\
    \ve{I}_B &= \frac{\ve{U}_{BN}}{\ve{Z}_{ph}} = 5.9418\phase{-177.52} \, \text{A} \\
    \ve{I}_C &= \frac{\ve{U}_{CN}}{\ve{Z}_{ph}} = 5.9418\phase{62.48} \, \text{A}
\end{align}

\textbf{Verification for star connection:}
\begin{equation}
    I_L = I_{ph} = 5.9418 \, \text{A} \quad \checkmark
\end{equation}

\subsubsection{Step 5: Neutral Current}

For a balanced system, the neutral current should be zero:

\begin{equation}
    \ve{I}_N = \ve{I}_A + \ve{I}_B + \ve{I}_C
\end{equation}

Converting to rectangular form:
\begin{align}
    \ve{I}_A &= 5.9418\phase{-57.52} = 3.1963 - j5.0309 \, \text{A} \\
    \ve{I}_B &= 5.9418\phase{-177.52} = -5.9256 - j0.2564 \, \text{A} \\
    \ve{I}_C &= 5.9418\phase{62.48} = 2.7293 + j5.2873 \, \text{A}
\end{align}

Sum:
\begin{equation}
    \ve{I}_N = (3.1963 - 5.9256 + 2.7293) + j(-5.0309 - 0.2564 + 5.2873) \approx 0 + j0 \, \text{A}
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
    \boxed{|\ve{I}_N| \approx 0 \, \text{A}} \quad \checkmark
\end{equation}

This confirms the system is \textbf{balanced}.

\subsubsection{Step 6: Power Per Phase}

Power factor:
\begin{align}
    \cos \varphi &= \cos(57.52^\circ) = 0.5369 \\
    \sin \varphi &= \sin(57.52^\circ) = 0.8437
\end{align}

Active power per phase:
\begin{equation}
    P_{ph} = U_{ph} \cdot I_{ph} \cdot \cos \varphi = 132.79 \times 5.9418 \times 0.5369 = \SI{423.82}{W}
\end{equation}

Reactive power per phase:
\begin{equation}
    Q_{ph} = U_{ph} \cdot I_{ph} \cdot \sin \varphi = 132.79 \times 5.9418 \times 0.8437 = \SI{665.76}{VAR}
\end{equation}

Apparent power per phase:
\begin{equation}
    S_{ph} = U_{ph} \cdot I_{ph} = 132.79 \times 5.9418 = \SI{789.10}{VA}
\end{equation}

\textbf{Verification:}
\begin{equation}
    S_{ph}^2 = P_{ph}^2 + Q_{ph}^2 = 423.82^2 + 665.76^2 = 622638.8 \, \text{VA}^2 \quad \checkmark
\end{equation}

\subsubsection{Step 7: Total Three-Phase Power}

\textbf{Method 1: Using per-phase values}

\begin{align}
    P_{3\varphi} &= 3 \times P_{ph} = 3 \times 423.82 = \SI{1271.46}{W} = \SI{1.271}{kW} \\
    Q_{3\varphi} &= 3 \times Q_{ph} = 3 \times 665.76 = \SI{1997.28}{VAR} = \SI{1.997}{kVAR} \\
    S_{3\varphi} &= 3 \times S_{ph} = 3 \times 789.10 = \SI{2367.30}{VA} = \SI{2.367}{kVA}
\end{align}

\textbf{Method 2: Using line values}

\begin{align}
    P_{3\varphi} &= \sqrt{3} \cdot U_L \cdot I_L \cdot \cos \varphi = 1.7321 \times 230 \times 5.9418 \times 0.5369 = \SI{1271.46}{W} \\
    Q_{3\varphi} &= \sqrt{3} \cdot U_L \cdot I_L \cdot \sin \varphi = 1.7321 \times 230 \times 5.9418 \times 0.8437 = \SI{1997.28}{VAR} \\
    S_{3\varphi} &= \sqrt{3} \cdot U_L \cdot I_L = 1.7321 \times 230 \times 5.9418 = \SI{2367.30}{VA}
\end{align}

\textbf{Verification:} Both methods give \textbf{identical results} $\checkmark$

\subsubsection{Step 8: Power Factor Correction}

Current power factor:
\begin{equation}
    \cos \varphi = 0.5369 = 53.69\%
\end{equation}

Required power factor: $\cos \varphi \geq 0.95 = 95\%$

\textbf{Status:} \colorbox{red!30}{CORRECTION REQUIRED!}

\textbf{Calculation of capacitor bank:}

Current angle: $\varphi_{\text{current}} = 57.52^\circ$

Target angle: $\varphi_{\text{target}} = \arccos(0.95) = 18.19^\circ$

Reactive power to compensate:
\begin{equation}
    Q_C = P_{3\varphi} \times (\tan \varphi_{\text{current}} - \tan \varphi_{\text{target}})
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
    Q_C = 1271.46 \times (1.5708 - 0.3287) = \SI{1579.59}{VAR} = \SI{1.580}{kVAR}
\end{equation}

Reactive power per phase:
\begin{equation}
    Q_{C,ph} = \frac{Q_C}{3} = \frac{1579.59}{3} = \SI{526.53}{VAR}
\end{equation}

Capacitive reactance:
\begin{equation}
    X_C = \frac{U_{ph}^2}{Q_{C,ph}} = \frac{132.79^2}{526.53} = \SI{33.49}{\ohm}
\end{equation}

Capacitance per phase:
\begin{equation}
    C = \frac{1}{2\pi f X_C} = \frac{1}{2\pi \times 60 \times 33.49} = \SI{79.32}{\micro\farad}
\end{equation}

\subsection{Results Summary}

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{lcc}
\toprule
\textbf{Parameter} & \textbf{Value} & \textbf{Unit} \\
\midrule
Inductive reactance, $X_L$ & 18.8496 & $\Omega$ \\
Phase impedance magnitude, $|\ve{Z}_{ph}|$ & 22.3453 & $\Omega$ \\
Impedance angle, $\varphi$ & 57.52 & $^\circ$ \\
Phase voltage, $U_{ph}$ & 132.79 & V \\
Phase current, $I_{ph} = I_L$ & 5.9418 & A \\
Neutral current, $I_N$ & $\approx 0$ & A \\
\midrule
Active power per phase, $P_{ph}$ & 423.82 & W \\
Reactive power per phase, $Q_{ph}$ & 665.76 & VAR \\
Apparent power per phase, $S_{ph}$ & 789.10 & VA \\
\midrule
\textbf{Total active power, $P_{3\varphi}$} & \textbf{1.271} & \textbf{kW} \\
\textbf{Total reactive power, $Q_{3\varphi}$} & \textbf{1.997} & \textbf{kVAR} \\
\textbf{Total apparent power, $S_{3\varphi}$} & \textbf{2.367} & \textbf{kVA} \\
\textbf{Power factor} & \textbf{53.69} & \textbf{\%} \\
\midrule
\multicolumn{3}{c}{\textbf{Power Factor Correction}} \\
\midrule
Capacitance per phase & 79.32 & $\mu$F \\
Configuration & Star & - \\
Reactive power compensation & 1.580 & kVAR \\
New power factor & 95 & \% \\
Apparent power reduction & 43.5 & \% \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{Complete results for Exercise 1}
\end{table}

