    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{Total system power triangle exercice3week4.pdf}
    \caption{Total system power triangle showing combined effect of all three phases. Overall system power factor is 91.94\%, which is acceptable but can be improved with individual phase correction.}
    
\end{figure}

\subsubsection{Power Factor Correction Comparison}

\begin{figure}[H]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{before after power factor percentage exercice3week4.pdf}
    \caption{Comparison of power factors before and after correction. Individual capacitors bring each phase to 95\% power factor. Note the different capacitor sizes required for each phase due to different loads.}
    
\end{figure}

\subsection{Importance of Neutral in Unbalanced Systems}

The neutral conductor plays a \textbf{critical role} in unbalanced systems:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Return path for unbalanced currents:} The neutral carries $I_N = 12.33$ A, which cannot return through the phase conductors.
    
    \item \textbf{Maintains phase voltages:} With neutral connected, each phase maintains $U_{ph} = 220$ V regardless of load imbalance.
    
    \item \textbf{Safety consideration:} If neutral is disconnected:
    \begin{itemize}
        \item The neutral point shifts from ground potential
        \item Lightly loaded phases experience overvoltage (can exceed 380V!)
        \item Heavily loaded phases experience undervoltage
        \item Equipment damage or failure is likely
    \end{itemize}
    
    \item \textbf{Sizing requirement:} The neutral conductor must be sized to carry the maximum expected unbalanced current safely.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Conclusions for Exercise 3}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item The system is clearly \textbf{unbalanced}, confirmed by significant neutral current ($I_N = 12.33$ A).
    
    \item Phase currents vary significantly: Phase A draws 17.05 A while Phase C draws only 10.10 A.
    
    \item Individual power factors range from 80\% to 100\%, requiring \textbf{phase-specific correction}.
    
    \item Overall system power factor is 91.94\%, which is acceptable for many applications but below the ideal 95\% target.
    
    \item Individual phase correction requires different capacitor sizes:
    \begin{itemize}
        \item Phase A: 83.11 $\mu$F (largest, lowest initial PF)
        \item Phase B: 54.09 $\mu$F (medium)
        \item Phase C: 20.49 $\mu$F (smallest, highest initial PF)
    \end{itemize}
    
    \item The \textbf{neutral conductor is essential} and must be properly sized. Disconnecting it would cause dangerous conditions.
    
    \item \textbf{Practical considerations:}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item Unbalanced loads are common in residential and commercial distribution
        \item Regular monitoring of phase currents helps identify imbalance issues
        \item Load balancing across phases should be considered during installation
        \item Neutral current can cause heating in distribution systems
    \end{itemize}
    
    \item Unlike balanced systems where calculations can be simplified, unbalanced systems require individual phase analysis with careful vector arithmetic.
\end{enumerate}




\section{General Conclusions}

\subsection{Summary of Key Findings}

This comprehensive analysis of three-phase systems has demonstrated fundamental principles applicable to power distribution and utilization:

\subsubsection{Exercise 1: Balanced Star System}

\begin{itemize}
    \item Confirmed the relationship $U_L = \sqrt{3} U_{ph}$ and $I_L = I_{ph}$ for star connections
    \item Verified neutral current equals zero for balanced loads ($I_N \approx 0$)
    \item Identified poor power factor (53.69\%) requiring significant correction
    \item Designed capacitor bank: 3 × 79.32 $\mu$F providing 43.5\% reduction in apparent power
    \item Demonstrated equivalence of per-phase and line calculation methods
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Exercise 2: Balanced Delta System}

\begin{itemize}
    \item Verified $U_{ph} = U_L$ and $I_L = \sqrt{3} I_{ph}$ for delta connections
    \item Observed 30° phase shift between line and phase currents
    \item Analyzed capacitive load with leading power factor (74.99\%)
    \item Confirmed delta-star transformation: $\ve{Z}_Y = \ve{Z}_{\Delta}/3$
    \item Demonstrated power equivalence between delta and star configurations
    \item Highlighted that capacitive loads supply reactive power (negative Q)
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Exercise 3: Unbalanced Star System}

\begin{itemize}
    \item Calculated significant neutral current (12.33 A) proving system imbalance
    \item Analyzed three different loads with power factors ranging from 80\% to 100\%
    \item Achieved overall system power factor of 91.94\%
    \item Designed individual phase correction with varying capacitor sizes
    \item Demonstrated critical importance of neutral conductor in unbalanced systems
    \item Showed dangers of neutral disconnection (voltage imbalance)
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Comparative Analysis}

