\subsection{Fundamental Relationships Verified}

Throughout this analysis, we have consistently verified these essential relationships:

\textbf{Star Connection:}
\begin{align}
    U_L &= \sqrt{3} \, U_{ph} \\
    I_L &= I_{ph} \\
    I_N &= \sum \ve{I}_{phase} = 0 \quad \text{(balanced only)}
\end{align}

\textbf{Delta Connection:}
\begin{align}
    U_L &= U_{ph} \\
    I_L &= \sqrt{3} \, I_{ph} \\
    \text{Phase shift} &= 30^\circ
\end{align}

\textbf{Three-Phase Power (Balanced):}
\begin{align}
    P_{3\varphi} &= \sqrt{3} \, U_L \, I_L \, \cos \varphi = 3 \, U_{ph} \, I_{ph} \, \cos \varphi \\
    Q_{3\varphi} &= \sqrt{3} \, U_L \, I_L \, \sin \varphi = 3 \, U_{ph} \, I_{ph} \, \sin \varphi \\
    S_{3\varphi} &= \sqrt{3} \, U_L \, I_L = 3 \, U_{ph} \, I_{ph}
\end{align}

\textbf{Delta-Star Transformation:}
\begin{equation}
    \ve{Z}_Y = \frac{\ve{Z}_{\Delta}}{3}
\end{equation}

\subsection{Practical Engineering Insights}

\subsubsection{Power Factor Correction}

Power factor correction is essential for:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Reducing utility penalty charges (typical requirement: PF ≥ 0.95)
    \item Minimizing conductor losses ($I^2R$ losses)
    \item Reducing voltage drops in distribution lines
    \item Increasing system capacity without infrastructure upgrades
    \item Improving voltage regulation
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Key decision:} Star vs delta connection for capacitor banks
\begin{itemize}
    \item Star: Lower voltage per capacitor, easier isolation
    \item Delta: Higher reactive power for same capacitance, no neutral required
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Balanced vs Unbalanced Systems}

\textbf{Balanced systems} (Exercises 1 \& 2):
\begin{itemize}
    \item Simplified analysis using symmetry
    \item Zero neutral current
    \item Uniform loading of phases
    \item Ideal for motor loads and industrial applications
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Unbalanced systems} (Exercise 3):
\begin{itemize}
    \item Require individual phase calculations
    \item Significant neutral current (must be properly sized!)
    \item Common in residential/commercial distribution
    \item Need regular monitoring and load balancing
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Connection Type Selection}

\textbf{Star (Y) connection preferred when:}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Neutral connection needed (lighting, single-phase loads)
    \item Lower phase voltage required
    \item Unbalanced loads expected
    \item Distribution systems (e.g., 400/230V)
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Delta ($\Delta$) connection preferred when:}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Higher current capacity needed at same voltage
    \item Motor windings (starting methods)
    \item No neutral required
    \item Balanced three-wire transmission
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Safety Considerations}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Never disconnect neutral} in unbalanced star systems:
    \begin{itemize}
        \item Can cause overvoltage on lightly loaded phases
        \item May destroy equipment rated for phase voltage
        \item Creates shock hazard
    \end{itemize}
    
    \item \textbf{Proper sizing} of neutral conductor:
    \begin{itemize}
        \item Must handle maximum unbalanced current
        \item In some cases, may need same size as phase conductors
        \item Consider harmonics in modern systems (can increase neutral current)
    \end{itemize}
    
    \item \textbf{Capacitor bank protection:}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item Discharge resistors required
        \item Overcurrent protection for each unit
        \item Voltage rating with safety margin
    \end{itemize}
    
    \item \textbf{Regular monitoring:}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item Phase current imbalance
        \item Neutral current magnitude
        \item Power factor trends
        \item Voltage levels on all phases
    \end{itemize}
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Economic Considerations}

Power factor improvement provides tangible economic benefits:

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{lcc}
\toprule
\textbf{Benefit} & \textbf{Typical Savings} & \textbf{Payback Period} \\
\midrule
Avoided utility penalties & 10-30\% of bill & Immediate \\
Reduced conductor losses & 5-15\% & 1-3 years \\
Increased transformer capacity & 20-40\% & N/A (avoided cost) \\
Extended equipment life & Variable & Long-term \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{Economic benefits of power factor correction}
\end{table}

