The MATLAB scripts developed for this analysis demonstrate:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Efficient complex phasor calculations
    \item Automated verification of relationships
    \item Professional visualization of results
    \item Parametric analysis capability
    \item Reusability for similar problems
\end{itemize}

These tools are essential for modern power system engineers, enabling rapid "what-if" analysis and design optimization.

\subsection{Final Remarks}

Three-phase power systems are fundamental to modern electrical infrastructure. This analysis has demonstrated:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item The mathematical relationships governing three-phase systems are consistent and verifiable
    \item Both balanced and unbalanced conditions require thorough understanding
    \item Power factor correction is both technically necessary and economically beneficial
    \item Proper selection of connection type (star/delta) depends on application requirements
    \item Safety considerations, especially regarding neutral conductors, are paramount
\end{enumerate}

The combination of theoretical analysis, numerical computation (MATLAB), and practical design (capacitor banks) provides a complete framework for three-phase system engineering.

\textbf{Key takeaway:} Three-phase systems are not merely an academic topic but the foundation of how the modern world is powered. Understanding their operation, analysis, and optimization is essential for any electrical engineer.

\subsection{Future Considerations}

Modern power systems face new challenges:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Harmonics from non-linear loads (rectifiers, LED lighting, variable drives)
    \item Renewable energy integration (solar, wind)
    \item Smart grid technologies and real-time monitoring
    \item Energy storage systems
    \item Electric vehicle charging infrastructure
\end{itemize}

All of these build upon the fundamental three-phase principles demonstrated in this report.

